plusCode.compoundCode: QJW3+VV Northern Waterfront, San Francisco, CA, USA
displayName.text: La Mar Cocina Peruana San Francisco
editorialSummary.text: Celeb chef Gastón Acurio serves Peruvian seafood in a large, partially outdoor space on the pier.
generativeSummary.overview.text: Upscale, waterside venue serving Peruvian cuisine such as ceviche and lomo saltado.
generativeSummary.description.text:
Upscale Peruvian eatery set on Pier 1 1/2 in the Embarcadero neighborhood with bay views.
The large venue features a bar and outdoor seating on the waterfront patio. It's popular for lunch and dinner, and reservations are recommended. People say the staff is attentive.
The menu focuses on seafood. Popular dishes include empanadas, ceviche, and lomo saltado. Guests also like the pisco sours and the desserts.
Visitors praise the location, the atmosphere, and the views.
Customers typically spend $50–100.

Nestled in the heart of San Francisco, this Greek gem offers an authentic taste of Greece with a cozy and welcoming atmosphere. From the moment I stepped in, the staff greeted me warmly and provided excellent service throughout the meal.

To start, I tried the Grilled Octopus, which was tender and perfectly seasoned, providing a wonderful balance of flavors. For my main course, I opted for the Lamb Chops. They were cooked to perfection, with a juicy and succulent texture that melted in my mouth. Each bite was a testament to the restaurant’s commitment to quality and authenticity.

The ambiance at Kokkari is cozy yet elegant, with a rustic decor that makes you feel right at home. The gentle lighting and meticulous attention to detail add to the dining experience, making it perfect for both intimate gatherings and larger celebrations.

I finished my meal with a serving of Baklava, which was the perfect way to end the evening. The layers of pastry were crisp, and the sweetness was just right.

Overall, Kokkari Estiatorio exceeded my expectations. With its outstanding cuisine, attentive service, and charming atmosphere, it’s a place I would highly recommend to anyone looking to indulge in a memorable Greek dining experience. plusCode.compoundCode: QJV3+XP Embarcadero, San Francisco, CA, USA
editorialSummary.text: Contemporary, family-style outlet serving Cantonese-style dishes with panoramic harbor views.
generativeSummary.overview.text: Traditional Chinese cuisine, including Peking duck and seafood, plus cocktails and a patio.
generativeSummary.description.text:
Upscale Chinese restaurant in the Embarcadero Center offering authentic, award-winning Cantonese cuisine.
The extensive menu features traditional fare like Peking duck, plus dim sum and fresh seafood. It's especially known for its black cod.
There's a bar and a lounge, and the restaurant is popular for special occasions. People praise the service and the bay views.
Customers typically spend $50–100.

editorialSummary.text: Contemporary waterside seafood eatery serving local oysters and clams, plus craft cocktails.
generativeSummary.overview.text: Casual Ferry Building restaurant and bar serving oysters and seafood specialties, such as fried anchovies and oyster po' boy sandwiches.

We both had a Crab cocktail to start which was hassle free (crab is just the leg meat, no need to crack shells) the cocktail sauce has a little extra horse radish in it and is definitely home made.

We had about 3 servings of bread, it’s a sourdough of sorts, but with a darker crust… it’s hard to stop eating… after the crab cocktail we did an order of the fried calamari… wow.. what a treat, the tartar sauce is also homemade and has a delicious flavor and chunky consistency, some of the best I’ve had in the city… it paired perfectly with the cocktail sauce… the calamari was the rings and full tentacle type, not the steak… and was perfectly breaded and lightly fried… felt good after eating it, not bogged down by grease, what a treat.

Finally we had the Cioppino which came with everything the traditional dish would come with, we split it and each had our own piece of garlic bread that came with the dish. The seafood was delicious, you could tell that the ingredients were fresh and the chef has made this dish a hundred thousand times… the sauce was mouth watering, very full of spices and aroma… would eat here a hundred times a year if I could.

A couple of beers and a manhattan with the food described above came out to $200 after tip and the server threw in a free dessert for the birthday boy.

5 stars, highly recommend what they claim to be the oldest restaurant in the city, established 1849.

plusCode.compoundCode: QJR2+FV Financial District, San Francisco, CA, USA
editorialSummary.text: Modern spot for Mediterranean eats in an upbeat atmosphere, plus happy hour and patio seating.
generativeSummary.overview.text: Mediterranean eats such as spiced beef dumplings and shakshuka offered in a trendy space.
generativeSummary.description.text:
Upscale Mediterranean restaurant in the Financial District with a bar, outdoor patio, and happy hour.
The menu features dishes from Southern France, Spain, Tunisia, and the Middle East. People recommend the lamb, falafel, and barcha spreads, as well as the drinks.
Guests praise the ambiance and attentive staff. Reservations are recommended.
Customers typically spend $50–100.

plusCode.compoundCode: QJV4+6P Embarcadero, San Francisco, CA, USA
editorialSummary.text: Chinese restaurant in the Rincon Center presenting dim sum in a warm, well appointed dining room.
generativeSummary.overview.text: Relaxed venue for dim sum, including steamed and fried options, with vegetarian and gluten-free items.
generativeSummary.description.text:
Trendy dim sum restaurant in the Embarcadero's Rincon Center Garage serving Chinese comfort food for breakfast, brunch, lunch, and dinner.
The menu includes vegetarian and gluten-free options, plus small plates and desserts. Peking duck, soup dumplings, and custard tarts are popular dishes. There's a great tea selection, as well as beer, wine, and cocktails.
The lively atmosphere is good for kids, and the restaurant provides high chairs. There can be a wait; reservations are recommended for lunch. People say service is fast.
Customers typically spend $30–50.

plusCode.compoundCode: QJR2+F9 Financial District, San Francisco, CA, USA
editorialSummary.text: Sleek, counter-serve chain known for its grilled cheese, burgers, mac & cheese & fries.
generativeSummary.overview.text: Angus-wagyu blend burgers, gourmet grilled cheese sandwiches, and other comfort dishes in casual surrounds.
generativeSummary.description.text:
Branch of a chain restaurant inside 455 Market in the Financial District serving American comfort food.
The menu includes quick bites and late-night fare, and features vegetarian and organic items. There's a kids' menu as well. People like the burgers, grilled cheese, and shakes.
The counter-serve setup has a casual ambiance that's good for kids. Guests praise the staff.
Customers typically spend $10–20.

plusCode.compoundCode: QJQ2+W7 Financial District, San Francisco, CA, USA
editorialSummary.text: Classic dim sum served from carts is the main draw at this bustling Chinese standby.
generativeSummary.overview.text: Casual, popular restaurant serving a variety of Cantonese dishes including specialty dim sum.
generativeSummary.description.text:
Upscale dim sum restaurant in the Financial District.
Popular dishes include chicken feet, pork and shrimp dumplings, and egg custard tarts. There's also a good tea selection. The eatery offers lunch, brunch, and dinner, and caters to vegetarians and those with gluten sensitivities. It's a good place for kids and solo diners.
The vibe is relaxed but trendy, and there can be a wait; reservations are recommended. Service is fast.
Customers typically spend $30–50.

reviews:
[{'name': 'places/ChIJzcayqEyBhYARyvjdWRk5_0E/reviews/ChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTURRN3NMZ0lnEAE', 'relativePublishTimeDescription': 'a week ago', 'rating': 5, 'text': {'text': "A wonderful, high-level restaurant. Probably the tastiest steaks among all the dishes we've tried in San Francisco.

Located in the center, with a convenient location. It's worth noting that despite the truly high level, the staff at this restaurant is very polite, attentive, and well-trained.

It’s a good idea to make a reservation in advance – the place is quite popular. The interior captivates with its blend of style and well-thought-out space planning. Every table offers a cozy atmosphere.

Special compliments to the dishes! Even the standard ones have a unique flavor, the chef pays attention to the details, and it’s very noticeable. Everything is delicious! Despite the amazing steaks, we especially remember the burata with beets – an interesting and tasty combination! 10/10, highly recommended!", 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': "A wonderful, high-level restaurant. We had plans for night time so we came during the brunch hours because we were craving some good steak for a while. What’s better than coming to a steakhouse for steak right?

We walk in and the lady checking us in was very cold and unwelcoming. We had to tell her we had a reservation she didn’t even greet us or anything. That set the tone for the experience. Our server was kind and helpful, didn’t feel like she was going above and beyond, just doing the bare minimum necessary- which for the price range is a little disappointing.

Oysters were great! Sparkling and white wine were great. Steak was disappointing… it was very chewy and not good quality meat. We were both disappointed with our experience because everything in terms food was good except the steak.

Would not recommend coming here personally if you are spending $300+ and receiving condescending service and chewy steak. Maybe we got unlucky because we came during brunch time but we are not coming back and letting our friends know to stay clear as well.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'My boyfriend and I came here for our anniversary.
